{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":232910,"duration_api_ms":347243,"num_turns":24,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"607036ef-fdd7-4d6d-b3c7-50a7bf8d1ed7","total_cost_usd":1.2499368000000004,"usage":{"input_tokens":15,"cache_creation_input_tokens":51865,"cache_read_input_tokens":644481,"output_tokens":7382,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":51865,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":15,"outputTokens":7382,"cacheReadInputTokens":644481,"cacheCreationInputTokens":51865,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.8310217499999999,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":389,"outputTokens":18315,"cacheReadInputTokens":2022198,"cacheCreationInputTokens":99785,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.4189150500000001,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"amendments":[{"body":"`unique_terminal_replay_match`, `is_legacy_start_for`, and `is_superseded_legacy_start` in `src/adapters/fs.rs` (lines 2748-2773, 2606-2615, 2596-2604) are still present and actively used in the `update_task_run` code path (line 3001). The spec explicitly requires removing `unique_terminal_replay_match` and all `started_at`-based disambiguation. The `fail_legacy_runless_entries` migration function was added as a pragmatic alternative, but it does not eliminate these code paths — it only marks runless Running entries as Failed on first write. The `update_task_run` fallback at lines 2990-3015 still uses `started_at` filtering (line 2999) combined with `unique_terminal_replay_match` to resolve completion of legacy entries. Either remove these functions as specified, or formally document in the spec that the backward-compat collapse pipeline and terminal replay matching are intentionally retained (with rationale), rather than leaving an undocumented deviation.","rationale":"The spec lists `unique_terminal_replay_match` and `started_at`-based disambiguation as explicit removal targets under Issue #2. Retaining them without spec acknowledgment means the stated acceptance criterion ('all runless matching/backfill code is removed') is not met. Future reviewers will keep flagging this as non-compliant."},{"body":"No tests exist for `fail_legacy_runless_entries` (fs.rs:2708-2719). This function modifies on-disk state (marks legacy running entries as failed and writes them out) and is called on every `record_task_run_start` and `update_task_run` invocation. The spec requires 'New tests cover each fix.' Add at least: (1) a test that writes legacy runless Running entries to ndjson, calls `record_task_run_start`, and verifies the legacy entries are failed with the correct outcome_detail; (2) a test that verifies already-terminal legacy entries are NOT modified; (3) a test that verifies the new run proceeds normally after legacy repair.","rationale":"This is untested mutation logic that runs on every write path. A regression here (e.g., accidentally failing entries that DO have run_id, or failing to write the repaired state) would corrupt milestone data silently."},{"body":"`fail_legacy_runless_entries` uses the caller's timestamp (`started_at` from `record_task_run_start` at line 2819, `finished_at` from `update_task_run` at line 2944) as the `finished_at` for failed legacy entries. If the legacy entry's `started_at` is later than the caller's timestamp (e.g., clock skew, entries written out of order), the resulting `finished_at < started_at` on the failed entry creates an impossible timeline. Use `max(legacy_entry.started_at, now)` instead to guarantee chronological validity.","rationale":"While this is an edge case, timestamp inversion in persistent records can confuse any downstream code that assumes `finished_at >= started_at`, and it's a simple fix."},{"body":"In `record_task_run_start` (fs.rs:2819-2822) and `update_task_run` (fs.rs:2944-2947), if `fail_legacy_runless_entries` triggers, the entries are written to disk immediately. The function then continues and may write entries again at line 2924 or 3149. This double-write is unnecessary I/O and creates a brief window where the on-disk state has the legacy repairs but not the actual operation result. Track the `legacy_repaired` flag and fold it into the final `should_write` / write-path instead of writing immediately.","rationale":"The double-write is a minor performance issue but the real concern is the transient inconsistent on-disk state. If the process crashes between the two writes, the legacy entries are repaired but the actual start/update is lost. A single atomic write avoids this."},{"body":"`TaskRunEntry::same_attempt` (model.rs:298-311) still falls back to `started_at` matching when either entry has `run_id: None` (lines 306-309). This is used by `fail_superseded_running_attempt`, `is_superseded_legacy_start`, `is_legacy_start_for`, and the collapse pipeline. While the write paths now require run_id, this fallback means two entries with different run_ids but the same started_at that both have one None run_id would be considered the 'same attempt'. After the `fail_legacy_runless_entries` migration marks all runless running entries as terminal, the only remaining callers operating on live (non-terminal) entries should always have run_id present. Document this invariant with a debug_assert or add a comment explaining when the fallback is still needed.","rationale":"The `same_attempt` fallback is load-bearing for the legacy collapse pipeline but could cause subtle mismatches if any code path accidentally creates a runless entry in the future. A defensive assertion would catch that immediately."}],"summary":"The diff addresses the three issues partially. Issue #1 (journal struct deduplication) is fully implemented — structs are defined once in model.rs with Serialize+Deserialize, imported by fs.rs, with explicit field-by-field merge and round-trip tests. Issues #2 and #3 (required run_id and plan_hash) are implemented at the port boundary — both `record_task_run_start` and `update_task_run` take `run_id: &str`, and `record_task_run_start` takes `plan_hash: &str`. However, the spec-mandated removal of `unique_terminal_replay_match`, `is_legacy_start_for`, `is_superseded_legacy_start`, and `started_at`-based disambiguation was NOT done — instead a `fail_legacy_runless_entries` migration strategy was added. This is arguably better engineering for backward compat but deviates from the spec without acknowledgment. The new `fail_legacy_runless_entries` function lacks test coverage despite being called on every write path. There's also a double-write issue where legacy repair is flushed to disk before the actual operation, creating a crash-inconsistency window."},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"59dd1225-81c3-47bd-ade5-9d0c99762754"}
